The Menu of a Fatty Child: It Does Not Breakfast and Eats to Dinner
More than a third of children from 9 to 13 have problems with obesity, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that obese children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
This shows once again how important it is for a person’s healthy development to be the environment in which he grows up and are the examples that surround him.
On the tables of obese children, sausages are up to half more often on the table than in families where normal-weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had French fries on the eve of the Enlightenment campaign under the motto "Adiposity is not a coincidence" for the evening meal.
In families with dickerchen, sport is not exactly one of the favourite occupations, however, as does the majority of today’s students – only 15 percent responded that their parents find time for active movement at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, with nearly 900 children from primary schools across the Czech Republic being surveyed.
This was already the second year of the action "Adiposity is not a coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Fund and the Unilever Society.
So far, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th classes participated in the project.
Unhealthy diets and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the frighteningly increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
“For example, only half of the children surveyed said they ate breakfast-second breakfast-meal-vesper supper five times a day—one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet in the breakfast-second-meal-vesper-event-break mode—one of the survey results.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative little things, such as the family’s regular breakfast time, are important for the healthy development of a child.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the students’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone eats breakfast alone.
Worst of all was the finding that in every tenth family is not breakfast at all.
Breakfast is considered to be the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
The survey showed, among other things, that people in the families of overweight children often consume unhealthy French fries.
And almost everyone - regardless of weight - drinks sweet lemonades every day (70 percent)
Although more than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sports, only less than half of their parents do – namely, only 15 percent.
Create your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to compose their own meal plan from offered possibilities according to appetite and opinion.
“What Czech children between the ages of 12 and 15 prefer in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite dishes were many flour dishes, meat dishes and of course sweets.
“Alarming is, above all, the great popularity of sweet lemonades,” the final report on this survey emphasizes.
At lunch, i.e. the main course, pasta won just in front of poultry.
The children almost didn’t like legumes and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Return to health
At the same time, however, the survey also showed that the children are quite willing to change their eating habits when they get the right information.
"In many cases, the control group of the survey participants who completed the questionnaire after completing the informative lecture "Adiposity is not a coincidence" saw a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy nutrition," the results of the project show.
This was obvious, for example, with the sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also crossed much more often on poultry or fish as the main dish of the day and were ready to eat less dumplings or sweet food.
