V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Review
The original carefree ride is caused by a series of completely avoidable, dilettant errors for the routine ride to the early shift.
Although it was possible to fulfill the ambitions for the most part, what good is it if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the store tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" aroused high expectations.
He promised to move the already year-old game series "Need for Speed" back into a new dimension and in the playable demonstration examples he actually seemed to be not only one of many action racing games.
We were also curious as to how the fitted passages, in which the main protagonist gets out of the car and continues on foot.
But as you’re used to with NFS, in the end, much is different than you’d expect.
Sure - potentially it's quite decent arcade races, but overall the game is narrowed by some superfluous bugs that have been present in this series for more or less a few years.
So they are actually no longer errors, but rather signs of a basically incomprehensible laziness of the game developers.
The adventure begins very well.
For the first time in history, the main character Jack has certain personal character problems; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, on the west coast, you sit on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea contains a whole series of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different track and that the individual stages take place in different, sufficiently different and interesting environments.
You don’t have the impression that the game would offer the same thing over and over again.
Some environments are still very nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the earlier parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the journey through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape seemed visually very pleasant.
From time to time, unusual elements bring a little variation to the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm that severely restricts sight.
In the mountains, on the other hand, you have to be hellishly careful not to be spilled by an avalanche.
By the way, the individual races are installed quite well one after the other.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to catch up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
And then there's the police who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty is passages in which Jack leaves the car.
It’s more about certain interactive animations where Jack flees from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
However, it is surprising that there are far fewer passages in the game than one would expect (in fact, only three).
Ultimately, this is more of a benefit to the game, because this element has at least no chance of getting bored - it is one of the elements that make the game more varied in the context of the above.
The driving model is in the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today’s point of view, it does not tear out trees, but on the other hand, one could not claim that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you have to look elsewhere.
But an action-packed racing will continue to be very well suited to the local driving model, although you could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in the best order.
Real problems only appear after a certain amount of time.
In contrast to the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
Of a game of this kind, it is hardly to be expected that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea before any impact on any object how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: When you overtake or pass on cars coming in, you "strip" the other cars only slightly in some places, but in other, almost identical situations you get into the spinning and spinning wild pirates.
Or drive the cart straight to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, this doesn’t matter anymore, it’s always annoying.
The restarts are solved in this way: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then you throw the game back to the last clue of the track.
Only - in every race you only have five restarts.
When you have exhausted them, everything starts from the front.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something fails, but you should rather not rely on it.
Sometimes, however, the restart doesn’t even help, as nothing else helps but to learn the critical section from the head.
Very unpleasant is that the same things often happen in the same places.
Some curves, for example, need to be traversed in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit through.
Elsewhere, you always meet "civil" cars in the same configuration at the appropriate location, whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see that the opponent comes past two cars in front of a playing, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive around or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, everything is designed to get to this situation always close to your nose.
The competitors have other advantages.
Throughout the game there are a few places where you are always overtaken in the same place by the same opponent and again here again without regard to the time.
The craziest thing is to finish the game on the long bridge, which you pass in the opposite direction.
The opponent must obviously get one out of here on the devil's side.
And if he is already in front of you, then of course he takes the view, so that you drive your own car in Klump a few times at first.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it quickly misses the joy of the game.
And that’s a shame, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is quite entertaining and in some places so action-packed that you almost no longer know where one’s head is.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "guilt" is about - the concept of fifty unique routes, the arrangement of races in a way that no boredom can arise, or something completely different...
An unusual idea is also the car change over the course of the races.
You should not miss the gas stations along the route, because this is where you can change the car, although in most cases the car you have right now is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for the urban areas, the strong American limousines for the straight highways and exotic super sports cars for the technical rides, for example on the serpentines in the mountains.
Hand in hand with the game history mode, the task mode (challenges) also goes – i.e. the races in the individual locations that you know from history.
Here there are not only medals, but also points of experience for your own profile, which is common for the tasks (challenges) and the history.
In order to get to the higher level of the driver, different items must be opened: from the car to the background for the profile.
This is simultaneously linked to the Autolog online feature, which among other things compares its own results achieved with those of other players and also provides additional collective features.
One of the more incomprehensible carvings is a situation in the last race of history.
Here you get by car to a subway tunnel (meeting), where you rest long in the dark on the rails (meeting).
On the tacho, numbers look between 150 and 200 km/h (means), but there comes at once from behind a subway and drives an uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial office we will probably argue for a long time about whether this was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think we are so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the visual overall impression is quite appealing in most cases and even brilliant here and there.
It is all the more annoying that at some exciting moments the refresh rate becomes slower and sometimes quite dramatic.
However, this is particularly true of accidents involving a greater number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use whatsoever.
The sound reproduction is as far as O.K. and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to a scale as wide as possible rather young audiences, a soundtrack was created a l<0xC3><0xA1> "of everyone something" - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
Need for Speed: The Run: Need for Speed: The Run: Need for Speed: The Run
If the game wasn’t narrowed by the above-mentioned totally unnecessary mistakes, we could have argued with the breast tone that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that’s how the game seems kind of unfinished.
In itself a great pleasure, but one should be prepared to see these errors with the power of airport lights.
