IBM history: From cheese cutters to space flights
Founded in New York a century ago, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name – Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
The name IBM was not adopted until 1924, when it was originally a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
IBM laid the foundation for the merger of four companies, whose history dates back to the 1980s.
They had technologies, such as the famous cutting-card clocks to register the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also held the chairmanship of the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition firm Thomas J. Watson to help him lead the company.
This leader then even shadowed IBM’s founders – based on Watson’s ideas, the company’s invincible culture and identity to this day.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM began, as the name suggests, with the manufacture and distribution of all kinds of machines for trade – from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades Watson led the company, he doubled its sales to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the executive chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under its leadership, IBM began to work on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM technicians and computers helped lead NASA’s flights into space – to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969, the famous flight of humans to the moon.
Meanwhile, in 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture - the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that set the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consultant part of PricewaterhouseCoopers and entered the business with high added value consulting services and services.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the concept of “Smarter Planet”.
