The Moved Pavilion
By Ingeborg Wiensowski
An architectural history with highs, lows and happy end: the Austrian World Exhibition Pavilion of Brussels won prizes in 1958, became a museum in Vienna, stood empty and got lost.
Now he is reopened as an exhibition house.
If modern post-war architecture swarms with clear shapes, glass halls, bold turns and new building materials typical of the belief in technical progress, then the Austrian pavilion of the architect Karl Schwanzer is an apt and famous example for the 1958 Brüssler World Exhibition.
Schwanzer’s pavilion was awarded the Grand Prix d’Architecture at the time for its light and floating steel-glass construction.
The construction is still considered a milestone in contemporary architecture.
He made the architect so famous that he also built Austria’s pavilion at the next world exhibition.
With his legendary BMW four-cylinder house plus bowl-like annex in Munich, he finally became internationally famous in 1973.
His pavilion, which was planned as a temporary exhibition building, had been erected after the world exhibition in the Swiss garden at the Wiener Südbahnhof, rebuilt and opened in 1962 a museum of the 20th century - the "20th House" it was called.
However, the building was neither spatially nor technically suitable as a museum - no walls for hanging art, no good climate.
Nevertheless, it was used until contemporary art in Vienna got a new house.
Since 2001, the building has stood empty and came down more and more.
Now the architect Adolf Krischanitz has rebuilt the pavilion, he is now called "21er Haus" and will be used in the future as a museum for contemporary art.
On Tuesday evening, the Belvedere Museum, to which the house belongs, opens the first exhibition there - a lucky case in every way.
Agnes Husslein-Arco, who became the new director of the Austrian Gallery Belvedere in 2007.
Husslein-Arco, a distinguished art historian with a considerable career, among other things in youth as an art painter, later at Sotheby's, the Guggenheim Museum and as founding director of the Museum der Moderne Salzburg, strongly enforced the reconstruction with politicians and monument protectors, procured public funds and private sponsorship funds and determined the use.
In addition to contemporary art, the works of the sculptor Fritz Wotruba were to be exhibited by the eponymous foundation, there was to be a café and a bookstore, and an office building had to be built for this purpose.
Strict supervision, small budget
Krischanitz was then the ideal cast for the performance.
Not only because he had sensitively rebuilt and expanded Joseph Olbrich's Secession in Vienna and won the competition, but because he studied at Schwanzer at the Technical University of Vienna and the pavilion for him was an "immeasurable place" where he had viewed the exhibitions "almost every weekend".
He knew the original design, and he knew the problems of the building, which already lost in its transfer to Vienna and its re-use in generosity and ease.
There were far greater problems with the current reconstruction: the building was "an energy slinger," says Krischanitz.
The window profiles of the glass fa<0xC3><0xA7>ade were replaced, glass fiber-reinforced insulating glass was used and the glass roof was replaced by special safety glass.
Cold bridge steel supports have been reinforced or replaced, and asbestos-filled ceilings have been renovated.
Two basements provided space for the new use, a lowered light trench between the house and the road provides for the exposure, a bridge leads to the entrance - almost a new building, but still the light Schwanzer Pavilion.
The original exterior doors have remained, the house is painted in the old red-brown rust protection shade.
And the cinema is still exactly as it used to be.
And all this under the strict supervision of the monument authority and with a small budget.
“Often, a material that is good and cheap had to be found and also liked the monument protection office,” says Krischanitz, pointing to a sloping floor in the basement.
Despite all the constraints, problems and alterations, the building has remained flexible and light.
It was difficult with the pavilion that “came out of Brussels,” Krishanitz recently said, a typical “drop-in-the-city story.”
Such an architecture is "always in the wrong place" and still wants "to raise a proper awareness".
In this case, however, the 21st house is not in the wrong place, because there has been an urban development lucky case: around the Swiss garden, the completely new planned "main station quarter", with office and residential buildings is being created.
And another good luck may come: the 21st house could get reinforcement from another Krischanitz building, because the collector Francesca von Habsburg bought the Berlin Temporary Kunsthalle, and, as you can hear, she is already negotiating with the city for a neighboring location in the Swiss garden.
