He then takes responsibility for the strategy of a bank, which has just proven once again that it has long earned the title of "Europe's largest scandal bank".
Because UBS is huge on the one hand - until recently it was the largest asset manager in the world - and on the other hand it has been glaring from one scandal to the next for years.
Nothing, it seems, is spared the once so proud Swiss bank.
It started in the financial crisis.
Until 2007 UBS had an excellent reputation.
The image of the silent and solid, but also exhausted Swiss asset manager had combined it with ambitious goals: it also wanted to become a very big number in investment banking.
For example, UBS managed more money than any other bank in the world with $1.6 trillion in 2007.
On the other hand, as an investment bank, she had advanced to the league of the largest banks in the world.
That made an impression.
The former banker and later long-time banking professor in Zurich Hans Geiger relates: "My students at the time I always presented UBS as a pattern of a good bank."
“From today’s point of view, you ask yourself: How could I be so wrong?”
He was greatly mistaken.
In 2007, it was revealed for the first time that something was wrong in UBS.
In the middle of the year, CEO Peter Wuffli resigned surprisingly, who until then was considered a highly intellectual and equally brilliant banker.
A few months later, they realized why he had left.
The bank’s investment division had swindled with subprime papers and had to write off billions.
To shoulder this, UBS announced a capital increase of CHF 13 billion.
To this end, she actually found investors, but some of them, until recently, would have shrunk their noses: an intransparent Asian state fund from Singapore and an Arab state fund that was so silent that one didn’t even know its name.
But that was only the first blow.
It got worse in April 2008.
The bank had to announce new billions of losses, Chairman of the Board of Directors Marcel Ospel, in 2006 the second highest paid Board of Directors of Switzerland, resigned.
In October 2008, the disaster followed: in view of their misinvestment in the financial crisis, UBS faced the collapse and had to be saved by the state.
The National Bank bought UBS for tens of billions of problematic securities, the Swiss Confederation gave six billion francs for a forced convertible bond, through which it could become co-owner of the bank.
The whole of Switzerland was shaken - because she noticed how dramatic it is for a small country when it houses such large banks.
Finally, the balance sheet total of UBS 2007 was more than five times that of Switzerland’s economic performance (see graph).
“Once again, we couldn’t save UBS,” said Geiger, a bank researcher.
The first disaster was followed by the second.
Just a few months later, UBS capitulated in tax dispute with America and agreed to release the data of wealthy customers who may have lashed behind taxes with the help of the bank.
In addition, she agreed to a $780 million payment – in return for unjustified profits from these transactions, including a fine.
UBS was more or less open to helping with tax evasion.
At the same time, she lost something that had always been her capital in the competition for rich customers: the Nimbus of secrecy.
After the scandal, the Swiss bank secret was no longer the same.
This was followed by the resignation of Chief Executive Officer and Chairman of the Board of Directors.
And the exodus of customer money.
Within a few months, the bank had lost its credibility in both central business areas: in investment banking through misspeculation and in asset management through the help of tax evasion.
And just as things got a little quieter, just as you thought, now the UBS is going to get it again, so follows this unspeakable dealer story: a single trader swindles 1.7 billion euros before the bank realizes that something is going wrong.
And it turns out: with risk management in investment banking, it obviously still doesn’t work.
“With the case of Adoboli, it has been found that risk control has not changed very much,” says Martin Janssen, economist and finance professor at the University of Zurich’s banking institute.
The chief financial officer of a large German bank is also certain: "The problem of UBS is that it does not control risk control."
It was the very idea of the caution with which the Swiss bankers had long ago started to become guardians of the great fortunes of the world: not too great risks, but security for money - might even collapse the world beyond the Alpine Republic.
The Swiss banks’ vaults have become a symbol of unwavering reliability, such as Lindt and Sprüngli for particularly fine chocolate.
The headquarters of UBS in Zurich still fits the cliché of the Swiss private bank - it's just a bit bigger.
The location is classic.
