The buildings here are magnificent, the store rents are among the highest in Europe.
Jewelers such as Tiffany's can be found here between Swiss traditional shops such as the Confiserie Sprüngli.
For centuries, Swiss banks have resided here: from the National Bank to the Palace of Credit Suisse to elite private banks such as Julius Baer.
The reception room of the UBS is accessed by a heavy revolving door.
Inside, the walls are marble-clad, in front of them are thick leather armchairs, next to the bank logo a large sign for the "Safe".
UBS knows what the customer is looking for here: Security.
This idea of the Swiss bank has displaced both Swiss major banks, UBS and Credit Suisse, but at some point – or betrayed, as the head of a small Swiss private bank finds.
He prefers not to read his name in the newspaper, after all, like all Swiss bankers, he also does business with the two big banks.
UBS has become too big, he finds - especially in investment banking, where the Anglo-Saxons had also spread.
The Swiss have nothing more to say.
"And if so, they have long since adapted to the customs of the Anglo-Saxons."
In fact, it was the Anglo-Saxon investment banking that changed UBS, gave it first high profits and then the debacle: no European financial institution has lost as much money in the subprime jungle as the Swiss big bank.
On October 15, 2008, the disaster became visible.
"On that Wednesday, the government coalition of the small seven million country decided on the largest rescue operation in the history of its nation," author Lukas H<0xC3><0xA4>ssig wrote in his book "The UBS Crash".
Up to CHF 68 billion or around EUR 45 billion, the politicians agreed to save the big bank facing bankruptcy.
How could this happen?
If you talk to Swiss bankers, they see the problem especially in the size of UBS.
In June 1998, two of the three Swiss major banks merged into a huge group.
