Hungry for growth, both the bank itself and a hedge fund founded before it invested in American subprime facilities.
It developed into a massive machine that packed and passed on securities on American mortgages, but also kept risks to itself.
Even when other banks were looking for a way out.
"Even in the summer of 2007, when the American real estate market was in flames, UBS bought there," says banking expert Geiger.
So big the euphoria, so deep the case.
One manager after another had to go as the attempts to clean up were more difficult than thought.
Posts at UBS became a spin seat and are still shaky to this day.
Whoever leads the big bank now has an almost impossible job.
He needs to find a strategy for a bank that has lost all the obvious business models.
Bank researcher Geiger already has an idea: end with investment banking, focus on asset management, return to the Swiss roots.
The bank does not want to go that far (yet).
But investment banking is supposed to shrink sharply, so much is already clear.
