Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before becoming the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent her anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who confessed to having committed a shooting in Norway in July, in which 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is by far not alone in cyberspace: he has spent a lot of time in front of his computer, chatting with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social networks.
After the tragedy of this summer, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It's easy - you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We found that it wasn’t hard to come to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recent report by the British idea factory DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, Bartlett says, that researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy — just as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then invited them with add-ons, but instead of linking to a new band or a new diet product, the Adds invited users to a survey asking about their educational status, their attitude towards violence, and the assessment of their own future.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to survey more than 10,000 supporters of 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their office once.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online supporters of far-right groups are mostly young, male and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, democratic, and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just one example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as in "likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, Facebook’s “Data Supernova” generates a research boom that has increased the number of scientific works with the name of this page in the title by nearly 800% over the last five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this site you can study people that you don’t usually reach with his clipboard on the street.
"If you tried to interview people of the British National Party in the past, it was very difficult to identify them."
“They had to inform the party first and it would never have allowed them to enter,” Bartlett said.
“On Facebook, it all falls away – you go straight to them.”
Others say the site provides a way to detect and resolve social health issues.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full-blown on Facebook tended significantly more to problem drinking than students who remained silent on this topic.
Moreno suggests that like-minded students, such as housing consultants, monitor the site and help a student if they post too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you didn’t recognize it,” said Dimitri Christakis, Morenos co-author and head of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
"We have found a way to identify vulnerable children who otherwise would not have been found."
Facebook is also constantly tapping on the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has compiled statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, voter turnout in the 2010 interim elections, and a National Happiness Index (using primarily data that only Facebook has access to – masters of digital freedom have long known that the site should make its large data base accessible to others for research purposes).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want it or not. In order to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, you allow the site to share your own personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know anything about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he investigated the public pages of students on Facebook.
"As far as she's concerned, it was just about her and her friends."
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline, there is no guarantee that a research participant is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how much of the information is true in a user profile and in posts.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn thinks that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
"Social research has to take care of the social - and a lot of social life is still taking place offline."
