7 Lessons From Interview With The Deceased Steve Jobs Shown In A Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, highlighting the engineering genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most revealing in the recently rediscovered job interview, which was dusted off in key markets this week before special film screenings, is how much this creative mind understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and self-proclaimed hippie, but he was also an meticulous organizer who eagerly crafted diagrams—a man who believed that many managing directors suffer from “a disease of thinking,” “that a really great idea constitutes 90 percent of the work... [but] there is an enormous amount of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product.”
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the television series "Triumph of the Fachidiots" about the break-up of the personal computer, and he spent more than an hour sitting with jobs in which they conducted one of the rare, in-depth conversations.
By that time, it had been 10 years since Jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he was already working hard on his new computer company NeXT, looking forward to the widespread adoption of the Internet.
While a small part of Cringley’s interview was used in specialist idioms, he says that the copy templates of the interview were missing in delivery.
It was only after Jobs’ death that a full VHS copy was discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly revised footage forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which will be released this Wednesday and Thursday at the Landmark Theatre.
For someone who is known to hate in-depth interviews, Jobs here seems surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
Over the course of the interview, there are four times longer breaks between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds of reflection, in which jobs clearly weigh their thoughts and strive for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs’ perfectionism comes to light when he seemingly impatiently responds to Cringely’s questions and urges him to respond more quickly to issues or side actions of greater importance.
Before the era of Pixar, iPod or iPhone recorded, the Lost Interview somehow seems incredibly far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies think is right or wrong and represents his own vision for the future of the computer.
It’s one thing to read posthumous appreciations of Jobs’ career, but seeing Jobs here as the eager dreamer who is on the jump to greatness is something completely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things can and should be.
Shortly after doing all this, he left and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a company:
"During all the years in business, I always ask, 'Why are you doing things?' and the answer you always get is, 'Oh, that's how it's done.'
No one knows why he's doing what he's doing.
That's what I found.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Astonishing how costs were recorded—mostly starting with “standard costs” that were quoted on mere assumption and then adjusted with “difference”—he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined to the very smallest extent.
How the Pope became obsolete:
Jobs tells of the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device that could sneak into the phone company and lead long-distance conversations in vain.
Much has already been written about the device, but Job’s enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-empowerment is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a toll-based phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
"We sent stuff a half dozen times around the globe and when you grumbled on the phone, it came out a minute later on the phone next door," Jobs said.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a giant thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs continues to tell of a glorious strike that Wozniak and he almost pulled off when they called via Blue Box in the Vatican in the middle of the night and wanted to talk to the Pope while they were as good as they could imitate Henry Kissinger.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the Pope himself came to the phone.
How he fell in love with technology (and called unprepared Bill Hewlett):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he searched for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs received a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
"That had a remarkable impact on me. It was the only company I had seen at that age and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees."
Later, Jobs became one of HP’s employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever made.”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with Braunscher tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang on to this machine and write programs for them.
How to improve innovation:
Several times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he built some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the whole computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had when developing a computer mouse:
"I remember striking arguments... they yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I got up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later, we had a mouse that we could have built for $15, which was incredibly credible.
About large companies that are slowing down:
Long before he brought Apple back to life, Jobs anticipated the ways in which so many industrial giants stumbled upon their visions and lost control of their stocks.
"Do we say you're working at IBM or Xerox, so you're making a better copy or printer, now and then?"
You own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [are it such people] who ultimately run the companies and the product that pushes people out of decision making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position is eradicated by the people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products - craftsmanship is necessary.
This is what happened with Xerox...
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
You could have been ten times bigger if Microsoft could have been in the 1990s.
You caught the defeat of victory.
About innovation as an art form:
“There’s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop that great idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about your intricacies.
You have to make votes, certain things you can’t, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5000 things, these concepts, and they all bring together...
Ultimately, it goes out to the taste, it goes out to the fact that one tries to deal with the best stuff that humans have created, and then tries to bring these things together into what one does.
Picasso said that good artists copy, steal great artists.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happened to be the best computer scientists in the world.
Had it not been the computer industry, they would create fantastic things in other areas.
