How to Detect a Lie
A look at the current headlines shows how questionable and widespread deception and lies are in daily life.
The Republican presidential candidate, Herman Cain, is working to master the allegations of sexual harassment on the part of several women, both sides accusing each other of lying.
Penn State's leadership is accused of perjury, allegedly withholding reports that a retired football coach sexually abused boys.
Last week, an open microphone was heard when French President Nikolas Sarkozy told US President Barack Obama that Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was a liar.
Lies destroy careers and shake countries.
New York Congressman and Internet exhibitionist Anthony Weidner made a fool of himself when he circulated denials that were very quickly refuted by incontrovertible evidence.
Former presidential candidate John Edwards is accused of campaign funding violations related to the cover-up of an extramarital affair.
And then, of course, no one who has experienced it forgets the media circus that President Bill Clinton triggered when he lied to the Oval Office about his sexual relationship with Monica Lewinsky during his second term in office.
Stories about school cheating and college exams are widespread.
There have been incidents where teachers have given their students the exam responses so that they can stand up for themselves in their performance reviews.
Mentors who should teach the opposite send a message that lying and cheating are okay.
How much deception do we experience?
As studies prove, we lie between 10 and 200 times every day.
However, many of these lies are considered to be emergency lies.
Another study shows that strangers lie to each other three times during the first 10 minutes of a meeting.
Identifying lies or "discovering lies" is one that is important for every person to learn, both for personal and professional reasons.
Far from a social game such as Sharades, where the goal is to call "Have You!", the defamation of deception is a serious field of knowledge based on scientific data collected over the past six decades at prestigious universities that conducted far-reaching research projects, especially in the fields of psychology and physiology.
One result of the research is that most of the ancient myths about lying have been debunked.
Lies look you in the eyes.
They stutter, stammer, blush, and do not always falter.
However, it should not be concluded that these liars are difficult to uncover and denigrate.
An experienced liar can penetrate to the truth by learning something about the structure of the claim, the fine facial expressions, about questioning and timing.
I have spent several years examining the scientific results of the extensive and steadily growing field of defrosting, and it is clear that defrosting a deception is a modern skill that is easy to learn and helps us in our complex world, especially if the hiring or questioning of persons or negotiations or administration is part of our own professional responsibilities.
Good liars are very good at estimating other people, awakening their interest and mastering their own emotions, and intuitively feeling how they are perceived by others.
Thanks to research, we know that extroverted people are more likely to lie than introverted people, that men are more likely to "self-centered" lies than women whose lies are more "orienting to others" - usually, they want to protect the feelings of others - that married people are less likely to lie to their partners than unmarried people (but the lies they tell are usually "fat").
We also know that if a person was exposed as an evildoer, others feel less guilty of lying to that person.
How do you know if someone is lying?
First, by observing the normal behavior of that person.
This is called "baselining", the starting position.
It provides a reference point for later evaluation of changes.
Observe the attitude, laughter, voice quality of their subject.
You should know better when someone is usually constantly tripping with their foot, so they don’t falsely accuse him of tripping with their foot during a meeting.
Then pay attention to accumulations of conspicuous verbal and non-verbal behaviors.
Consider these accumulations as alarm bells that scream, not as evidence of defrosting.
People who deceive may become more obstinate when they try to remember their story. Maybe their feet point towards the door or they lean towards the exit, change their position in a significant way, or show a "relaxation after the hiring conversation", this deep, relaxing exhalation and change in attitude when all the hard questions are over.
Askers often falsely signal that a hiring interview is over, just to keep an eye out for this relaxation after the hiring interview.
Also, pay attention to the language of your subject.
Scott Peterson’s slipper is famous when he used the past form when he claimed that his dead wife was still alive and triggered a national search for her.
Deceiving people can also use a distancing language: "I didn't have a sexual relationship with this woman... Miss Lewinsky" or if you repeat a tricky question in general.
The most common verbal signs are subtle.
Some people use "qualifying language" when answering a tricky question: "Well... to tell you the truth ... as far as I know ... to the best of my knowledge and conscience."
This makes the answer more perceptive than factual, which often makes the alarm bells scream.
There is no magic tool for defrosting lies, but you can learn skills that allow you to defrost.
Thanks to these skills, anyone less often can become a victim of fraud, both in private and professional life.
