The quintet included Costa Rica in its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
"Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true"
In the exclusive conversation with Viva, bassist Jeff Ament of Pearl Jam says the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts next Sunday at the National Stadium.
They were expected for more than 20 years, but the band assured them that they would make a dream come true when they play in Costa Rica.
The bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day they will perform at the National Stadium from 7.30 p.m. along with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You can read an excerpt from the conversation, the full transcript of which can be found in the online edition of La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream come true when Pearl Jam is playing in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what that means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I have only been to Costa Rica once for a vacation. It is such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few days.
It is exciting for us to bring our music there.
I ask you this because the fans of the band are completely devoted, they experience the days before the concert more intensely.
What do you say to your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for standing by our side all these years.
We took almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Doesn’t that put a bit of pressure on your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on a few huge shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
We really want to play there.
We love this country, we like to surf and love the jungle, and Costa Rica is one of the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone surfing to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico, these are excellent areas for surfing. In this way, about people who love surfing, we have learned about it.
With a view of the tour you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What plans do you have for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there, we don’t set any limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that's partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs, and each one likes a different song, so the decision we're going to play isn't easy.
If we include two or three songs that we haven’t played in a long time, we can maintain our concentration better and they surprise us because they remind us the reasons why we liked these songs, otherwise they could be forgotten.
That makes the show more interesting for us and I think, therefore, also for the audience.
With this tour, you will celebrate your twenty-year history.
When you look back, is it hard for you to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don’t think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band, even for over 20 years, which seems like a dream.
We also continue to rely on this blessing and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We like it and are excited to create music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places of the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't stand better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Occasionally, a band emerges from a city, but it is already unusual if five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud of it and feel honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We are still happy to be friends with all of them and we are honored to be part of this upcoming Seattle sound.
It’s also very unusual for a band like yours to stay with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) joined us 13 years ago. This alone is much more time than many bands survive.
First of all, I think we all appreciate being alive and also we care about each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical paths have opened up that give everyone the freedom to experiment.
One trusts the other and his music, and we couldn't be better off.
Your relationship with glory has not always been easy, but you have always been able to do what you wanted thanks to your success.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it’s too easy to miss out on this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you remember that people have come because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what it has created without being obsessed with being a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and at first it was great.
We were a band for three years that had never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have taken so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore) who set up the band with us. When I hear a song or see photos, I think about what an incredible man Andy was and how he made me laugh. It was always a pleasure to go to work, laugh together and talk about music.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas are responsible for opening the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know her works, especially Eddie Vedder, and the band have therefore chosen for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and this band liked us best. That is why we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. That will be exciting.
Why do you always change the text of Yellow Ledbetter when you play live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings it, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to mind.
Who influenced you as a bassist?
Of so many+
One of the first things I think about is Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fashion phenomenon?
I think we all don’t feel very connected with the word grunge.
When I think about it, the bands I mentioned before, such as Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and all the others that came up at the same time, are still important today, I think that’s great because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney are now making better music than ever before.
At first her music was darker, now she is more positive.
Why?
That’s interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit light-hearted, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have something positive in them.
Both of them came to me with tears when I heard Ed playing them, they're very dark songs.
I believe that as you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life – for example, if you lose a family member or a friend – that affects your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also think that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
