Asphalt from UNAM prevents potholes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the Mexican University of UNAM, develops polymer-modified asphalt to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs were taken into account from the road surface, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 potholes if the rainy season erupted in the Zona Metropolitana del Valle de México (the urban area of the valley of Mexico), Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, a researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (FQ) at the University of UNAM, warned and assured that if the laying out and the containment of the potholes would be significantly reduced, the amount of the water.
In his lecture "Battle holes from a technical point of view", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing asphalt modified with polymers to produce a mixture similar to the asphalt, which, however, has greater mechanical resistance both at high and low temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera said that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behaviour of road surfaces and thus avoid the occurrence of potholes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, one part of which has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes. Together, they give the road surface its characteristic elastic behaviour.
Tensile-elastic behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180° C., at 120° C., it is very viscous and almost solid at 50° C., while it becomes brittle at very low temperatures.
“This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in one day depending on weather conditions and temperature fluctuations,” the chemical engineer explained.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City had mostly a flexible road covering, composed of six layers of material, the last three of which included asphalt.
Between the top layers there is a wear layer of asphalt, which consists of small, paved asphalt and then solidified stones.
Every single stone of this wear layer had been bathed in asphalt.
When the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
“If it were modified asphalt, the forces would spread even better,” said the chemical engineer.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "a last layer is laid out, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since these layers are in contact with the vehicle tires, they require a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they must produce friction.
This road surface receives and distributes the most forces, the support layer also needs a reasonable thickness and the material it consists of must be maintained.
The weather conditions, especially humidity and temperature fluctuations, are further, important factors to consider, above all the water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain becomes wet, water penetrates the layer and only passes out again, causing a softening of all the layers of the road surface and as a result, the occurrence of potholes.
When a punchhole is created, he said, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only affected afterwards. But the damage is not immediately caused, but it is a process that would have to be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) stated that the vehicle load is another important cause of the occurrence of potholes, so the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this regulation is complied with in order to avoid frequent potholes.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that a lot of research was still waiting, for example on asphalt emulsions, which are already on the market in other countries, and with which the potholes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
