Energy policy:
Facts should win over dogmas
If there is an issue that cannot be dealt with on the basis of short-term considerations or emotions, this is certainly energy policy.
The availability and costs of electricity directly affect the purchasing power and the competitiveness of the companies.
It is reasonable to take an election meeting as an occasion to reflect on this issue and on the position of nuclear energy.
The debate will only bear fruit if it probes the overall economic, social and ecological consequences of the proposed options.
The French should base their opinion on objective facts, rational data.
Although there are 7 billion people on this planet, demographic evolution is driving a doubling of electricity demand by 2050, not a huge proportion of the world’s population should have to give up a vital element.
At the same time, the scarcity of fossil resources must be mitigated in order to continue to produce electricity without forgetting the imperative need to reduce greenhouse gas emissions, an issue that has disappeared from the ecological debate, in order to fight against climatic irregularities.
The Fukushima accident does not alter any of these parameters.
Therefore, Germany continues to remain isolated in its decision to renounce nuclear power.
This is not the case in Belgium, which submits its decision to the need to find a substitute source capable of substitution, nor in Switzerland, which just intends to build only last-generation nuclear power plants.
The United Kingdom, Finland, Poland, the Czech Republic, the Netherlands, Sweden, South Africa, China, India and Brazil, to name but a few states, continue to follow their projects with determination.
The United States, in turn, decided to join its park after Fukushima by relaunching the Three Mile Island plant, which had been shut down after the nuclear accident.
Even though the German model, which is geared towards renewable energy sources, is sometimes set as an example, the reality is contrary to the discourse.
The election in Berlin will be in the form of a reduction in the electricity price, an increase in energy dependence, particularly on Russia, due to the increased use of imported gas, an increase in CO2 emissions caused by gas and coal-fired power plants.
The totality of these unpleasant effects will become apparent within a few months.
The case of Denmark gives cause for thought.
Denmark, on the one hand, is a European leader in wind energy, from which it derives 30% of its electricity; on the other hand, it is one of the strongest users of coal and gas, used alternately with wind energy; as a result, its CO2 emissions and its electricity price are respectively 65% and 50% higher than the corresponding European average.
Thanks to the persistence of our energy policy, our neighbours pay a 40% higher electricity bill compared to our French households.
As the energy price in the globalised economy plays a key role in competitiveness as well as in the stability of industry on national soil, the French companies have an advantage in Europe because of the cheapest electricity.
Any significant reduction in nuclear power would therefore result in a strong increase in the price of energy, which would lead to the noble statements about the reindustrialization of our country and the defence of purchasing power becoming an illusion.
Surveys showed that this is a price that the vast majority of French people are not willing to pay as much as it shows resistance to the principle of this energy source.
Let’s face it, our country’s energy policy has enabled us to build an industry with 125.00 direct and 410,000 induced jobs.
Due to its strong export character, it brings a multitude of specialized small and medium-sized companies to the international markets and makes them the creators of countless jobs.
If France took the decision to step out of nuclear power, a large part of these SMEs would fall victim to it, and the annual 6 billion euros of investment goods and nuclear energy exports would shrink more and more.
Which electrician would hire an EPR designed to work for sixty years if the decline of its producer is pre-programmed?
To solve the energetic equation, one has to admit that there is just as little as a devil’s work a miracle tool for generating electricity.
The low-carbon solutions developed by Areva for the use of nuclear power and renewable energy testify to the complementarity of energy sources.
Maintaining the highest possible level of safety is an absolute imperative for nuclear power.
In France, we have a security agency that carries out uncompromising and transparent checks in existing works such as construction in Flamanville.
Their work teams, who have made a name for themselves because of their professionalism, are just obsessed with the security concept.
Within 50 years, the nuclear industry has experienced three serious incidents.
Only one, namely in Three Mile Island, has occurred under normal operating conditions; so it went without consequences for humans and the environment.
In Chernobyl, the drama was conjured up by reactor construction as well as inexhaustible human failure.
In Fukushima, some seem to forget that the accident was caused by two natural disasters that never existed, causing the death of several tens of thousands of people.
The nuclear industry will draw its lessons from this accident as it did after the two previous ones.
As a result of this approach, as well as a cooperation between the security authorities of the French and German operators and designers of nuclear power plants, the EPR is a design that enables it to resist such phenomena.
Since it is considered desirable for electrical engineers to build a nuclear power plant, a construction stop in Flamanville would be a fabulous gift to the competition of Areva and EDF by allowing them free path to take up the leadership position in the inevitable development of nuclear power.
It is essential and legitimate to look for the best energy bouquet for our country, but it would be irresponsible to have emotions, dogmas and party maneuvers dominate a debate that also determines the economic, social and financial situation of our country.
Is immigration a burden or a chance for the economy?
The immigration policy led by Nicolas Sarkozy has been criticized from many angles - overloading of police, judicial and administrative bodies due to a policy subject to numbers, compatibility of this policy with the status of a "country of human rights", as France itself had titled itself.
Recently, the harassment of foreign students had shaped the weekly shows on the official side, the Minister of the Interior had casually announced (see Libération of 23 May) that France "did not need any talents, masons or waiters from abroad".
But this policy was rarely analyzed from an economic point of view.
There is a broad consensus on this issue between the right and the left.
On the right, the tone was struck by Jacques Chirac, who declared in 1976 that "900,000 unemployed, including over 2 million immigrated workers, should not be a problem for a country", on the left by Michel Rocard, who had explained in 1990, France "could not absorb all the poverty of the world".
The only difference is the degree of generosity.
The fear of the invasion of the national soil by hordes of Polish plumbers was shared in 2005 by both right and left.
From both camps the immigrants were perceived as a burden on the economy and French society.
The only difference is the degree of generosity that immigrants are willing to admit.
Francois Hollande is limited in his program to banalities that point out that partnership development allows us to solve our "migration problems".
This idea of immigration as a burden, as a problem, may have an impact on the elections; however, it is economically costly.
As economic experts Ian Goldin and Geoffrey Cameron present us in a recently published work that summarizes the latest findings on immigration (Exceptional People: How Migration Shaped Our World and Will Define Our Future, May 2011, Princeton University Press, 352 p.), there is a broad consensus among the specialists regarding the positive impact of the immigrant flood on economic growth, wages and jobs.
Reducing immigration would defuse growth and harm the labour market situation.
The fears about the influence of migrants are based on the idea that they threaten to substitute the domestic workers, especially the less qualified ones, by exerting pressure on their wages.
Experience shows, however, that the immigrants are in fact much more complementary than the local wage earners, as they are mainly engaged in occupations in sectors that are technically unburdened.
The low-skilled immigrants work in sectors that do not attract local wage earners, the more skilled among immigrants work in dynamic sectors where training is not matched to the job offer.
Positive wage effect
Just as a surgeon would have difficulty working in a country where there is a shortage of anaesthetists, this complementarity also has a positive effect between locals and migrants on the influx of immigrants on wages and the domestic labour market situation.
Giovanni Peri has calculated in this way that a 1% increase in immigrant floods will result in a included, long-term increase in real wages between 0.6% and 0.9%.
And this without taking into account the fact that the diversity of ideas and economic growth brought by immigrants is beneficial (highly proportion of native immigrants among American Nobel laureates; Google, Intel, Paypal, eBay and Yahoo were founded by immigrants).
Migrants also contribute net to the social systems, in the European countries on average at around 1% of the total household.
The World Labour Organization estimates, for example, that a person who immigrates to Germany at the age of 30 brings in an average net contribution to the public budget over his lifetime (income minus expenditure) of around 150,000 euros.
Nicolas Sarkozy, at the start of his mandate, wished to bring about the missing intersections "with his teeth".
However, these said teeth, which should deter immigrants, achieved exactly the opposite effect.
