Nord Stream, new gateway to Russian gas in Europe
The Nord Stream gas pipeline, which runs on the Baltic Sea seabed and connects western Europe directly with Russia, has been put into operation.
It is designed to provide gas for an equivalent of 30 million households.
The Russian gas giant Gazprom wanted to celebrate this event with splendor and glory.
Over 500 invited guests, including four heads of state and government, attended the inauguration of the new Nord Stream gas pipeline, which connects Russia and Germany directly below sea level last Tuesday on the Baltic Sea coast under orchestral sound and at the gourmet buffet.
German Chancellor Angelika Merkel, Russian President Dmitri Medvedev, French Prime Minister Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon and his counterpart Mark Rutte from the Netherlands have symbolically jointly turned the wheel of the valve, which transports Russian gas into the Western European network.
With the new gas transmission, 27.5 billion cubic meters of additional Russian gas per year will be delivered to Western Europe by a first 1,224 km long pipeline connecting the Saint Petersburg region with Mecklenburg-Vorpommern.
A second pipeline, which allows a total supply of 55 billion cubic meters of gas - the equivalent of French total consumption - will be completed by the end of 2012.
And you already have the eventuality of building a third line on your own track.
For Gazprom, the timely and precise completion of this enormous building looks like a victory.
The project was highly controversial in Poland and the Baltic States.
The Nord-Stream pipeline will enable direct gas delivery to Germany, avoiding any route by third countries (Poland or Ukraine) on land.
For this reason, these two countries are losing a little of their power: it is now becoming more difficult for them to exert pressure on Russia by threatening to close access to Western European markets.
Warsaw, most engaged in the debate, was not shy away from comparing the North Stream pipeline with a "new German-Soviet pact" in connection with the alliance between Hitler and Stalin for the occupation of Poland in 1939.
This means that the issue is politically highly sensitive.
Western Europe has gained even greater security of supply through the support of this Russian project.
However, this is at the cost of de-energizing Europe, as the project has broken a gap between Western and Eastern Europeans.
In less than five years, Russia has managed to enforce its vision of a direct alliance between Russia and the rich Western countries, which have strong gas consumption and whose gas deposits are at a disadvantage.
"This gas pipeline is a component of our partnership with Russia, it is a new artery that connects us in an organic way," Fran<0xC3><0xA7>ois Fillon confirmed at the inauguration of the gas pipeline, pointing out the extent to which the major gas contracts are also important from a political and economic point of view.
All this explains the broad smile of the numerous Gazprom managers represented in Lubmin regarding the gas supply line.
The construction of this gas transmission is also an outstanding technique.
The underwater pipe is made of steel with concrete sheathing to protect it from ship anchors.
It rests on the seabed, about 200 m deep.
During its construction, mining fields dating from the Second World War had to be removed.
"About a hundred mines had to be carefully removed or destroyed," said Jens Müller, spokesman for Nord Stream.
In addition, increased measures had to be taken to protect the fauna and flora.
The line is a long line of metal, heavy like 242 Eiffel towers, which is not interrupted by anything over the entire length: neither valves nor maintenance stations.
A control platform was planned off the coast of Sweden, but the project managers refused, as the Swedes had little hope of seeing a Russian state company permanently settle on the level of their coasts.
“In the event of an accident, we close the gas passage in less than a minute,” Jens Müller said.
In the event of a leak, the gas located in the gas transmission thus escapes into the air.
However, this case is considered unlikely by the designers as the weld seams were estimated to withstand a leak per 100,000 years.
State monitoring of the gas transmission is ensured both by an underwater robot controlled for external observation purposes by a seagoing vessel, as well as by a device circulating inside the gas transmission.
It has the shape of a cigar, with a diameter of one meter, is introduced into the interior of the pipeline and is moved through the gas pressure.
After three full days of moving through the line at a speed of 3 meters per second, the device provides the most accurate information on possible deformations of the metal upon arrival.
The gas transmission was designed to work for fifty years without even having to undergo the slightest repair.
The gas circulation is easily ensured by pressure.
This is 200 bar at the access point, 100 bar at the exit point.
Five companies have united their forces to realize this project.
However, the pipeline remains in the hands of Gazprom, which holds 51% of the shares.
Furthermore, the German companies E. ON and BASF (each 15.5%), as well as the Dutch Gasunie and the French group GDF Suez (each 9%) are affiliated here.
These five companies have formed a corporate community called Nord Stream, which is responsible for the construction and operation of the gas pipeline.
It is based in Zug, Switzerland, where taxation is particularly favourable.
Gazprom then leased the entire capacity of its gas transport to this company, subject to a twenty-year renewable contract.
"Gazprom will pay for the total capacity, no matter how large the amount of gas that is actually transported is," Jens Müller said.
The financing of gas pipeline construction was secured to 30% by shareholders and to 70% by bank loans.
The total cost of work should be EUR 7.4 billion for both pipelines.
For GDF Suez, for example, the investment total was 240 million.
However, minority shareholders are willing to recover their expenses, since Gazprom alone bears the liability risk.
The gas pipeline emerges from the Baltic Sea on a sandy, pine-wooded stretch of coastline near Lubmin.
The 4.5-metre-high valves form the gas exit gate.
Sensors measure pressure, temperature and other key figures of the incoming gas before it is forwarded to the German gas pipelines.
Since last Tuesday, this terminal has been supplied with a million cubic meters of Russian gas per passing hour.
At full capacity, this would be 3 million cubic meters per hour and 6 million in 2012.
